        <a name="linux"></a> 
        <h4>1. What is Linux?</h4>
        <p>Linux is an operating system kernel initially created in 1991 by Linus 
          Torvalds (then a graduate student at the University of Helsinki in Finland). 
          The kernel acts as mediator for your programs (processes) and for your 
          hardware. It takes care of memory management for all running processes, 
          giving them access to processor cycles. The kernel also provides a portable 
          interface for processes to talk to your hardware. 
        <p>The Linux kernel was not particularly useful in and of itself -- to 
          be a fully functional operating system it needed a lot of programs such 
          as compilers, editors, and text formatters. It just so happened that 
          the <a href="http://www.fsf.org/" target="_blank">Free Software Foundation 
          (FSF)</a> had been undergoing a massive effort (since 1983) to develop 
          an operating system called GNU's Not Unix (GNU). By 1991, FSF had developed 
          everything needed for an operating system except for the kernel. 
        <p>In 1991, Linus combined the Linus kernel with the GNU System and finally 
          the world had a 100% <a href="http://www.fsf.org/philosophy/free-sw.html" target="_blank">free</a> 
          operating system. Both the GNU System and the Linux kernel were released 
          under the GNU General Public License (usually called the GPL). The GPL 
          is a &quot;free&quot; software license; this means free in the sense 
          of liberty not in the sense of price (think free speech not free beer). 
          It gives you the freedom to &quot;copy, distribute, study, change, and 
          improve the software&quot;. 
        <p><em>Although PLUG has chosen to refer to the GNU/Linux operating system 
          by the commonly accepted naming convention of Linux, we honor the fundamentally 
          important work that GNU has contributed.</em></p>
